ce:section.ce:para:
The potential prospective of RS@CQDs as the sensing probe for MSG has been investigated by monitoring the changes in the fluorescence emission spectrum of formed particles in presence of different kinds of metal ions and bio-molecules. The PL emission spectrum of developed RS@CQDs in the presence of chosen 14 ions including Ca2+, Mg2+, K+, Cu2+, Na2+, Fe2+, NH4
                        +, ascorbic acid, aspartic acid, citric acid, glycine, serine, cysteine and MSG has been illustrated in Fig. 4
                        A. The outcomes described that slight fluctuations were observed in the emission intensity of formed RS@CQDs with the addition of chosen ions. However, the PL emission intensity of RS@CQDs has been significantly quenched in the presence of MSG pointing towards the sensing aptitude of RS@CQDs for MSG. The availability of various functional groups such as hydroxyl and carboxyl moieties has served as an excellent chelating ligand for the complex formation with the biomolecules (
                           Figure S3
                        ). The development of non-fluorescent complex between the surface functional groups of formed RS@CQDs and MSG ions has resulted in the fluorescence quenching of nanoparticles. The quenching in emission intensity was caused by the effective and reversible electron/hole transfer process through the eradication of the electron/hole recombination phenomenon.[29] Moreover, the non-radiative electron transfer from RS@CQDs to MSG ions quenched the PL emission originated from the radiative recombination of excitons in RS@CQDs.[30] The addition of MSG ions to the RS@CQDs solutions did not generate fluorescence followed by the electron transfer channel which further supported the quenching phenomenon (Scheme 1
                        ).[31].

An effective fluorescence probe must have high selectivity. For this purpose, the MSG ions and a total of 13 distinct metal ions and biomolecules such as Ca2+, Mg2+, K+, Cu2+, Na2+, Fe2+, NH4
                        +, ascorbic acid, aspartic acid, citric acid, glycine, serine and cysteine were investigated for selectivity in order to assess the effectiveness of designed sensing methodology. The measurements were carried out by combining the various chosen molecules with a 50 μm concentration of MSG. The outcomes reflected the excellent aptitude of MSG to increase the level of quenching in the emission intensity of RS@CQDs in the presence of interfering ions. These results suggested that the produced RS@CQDs have remarkable selectivity and sensitivity irrespective of the presence of any other biomolecules and metal ions (Fig. 4C). The produced sensory probe in this work has clearly offered great selectivity and sensitivity towards MSG ions when compared to the prior available literature (Table 1
                        ). Our results have revealed that developed RS@CQDs have good potency and sensitivity for the detection of MSG ions.
